His successor was his younger son, Eochaidh Buidhe, the Eclzodz'ua Bm'de of Adamnan (36). Six kings of the family of Eochaidh successively occupied the throne. But the battle of Magh Rath, which was fought in 637, by Domhnall Breac, greatly weakened the kingdom, and the power os the family declined until 689, when the soeptre passed to the house of Loarn, in the person of Ferchar Fada (203). The supremacy remained with the house of Loarn for some time, but eventually was resumed by the raee of Gabhran, from which the genealogies derive the descent of Kenneth Mae Alpin, the annexer of Pictland, and his line, down to Alexander mac Alexander, the last male representative. On the other hand, from Ferehar Fada were deseended the ancient Momaors, or Stewards, of Moray, the senior representatives of the race. From him also came the powerful families of the Clann Guaz're or Maequarries, and Clann Fc'omzyzcz'n or Machinnons, and of whom there were such numerous monuments in Hy and Tiree. From Fer- char Fada came also the great family ofrllac Coimzfflz or Mackenzie⁵, in whom the. lordships of Seaforth and Kintal were afterwards vested. From him also came the
